entry.title: media/VideoEncodeAccelerator::Config: Add drop_frame_thresh_percentage
entry.content:
This CL adds |drop_frame_thresh_percentage| to

VideoEncodeAccelerator::Config. It indicates the percentage of the

target data buffer and when the data buffer fallows below the

percentage, a frame is dropped - no encoded chunk is produced for the

frame. If a client doesn't want to drop a frame, then the value must

be set to zero. The default value for it is zero.

This CL sets the value to zero in all the clients. So this CL doesn't

change the original behavior.



Design doc: go/frame-drop-VEA

entry.content:
No observable behavior change.

The controllers were originally merged in crrev.com/c/4517941 so

WEBAUTHN_CREDENTIAL would honor the PASSWORDS account storage opt-in.

With crrev.com/c/4874142, this is now guaranteed by

UserSelectableType::kPasswords mapping to both data types. So the

controllers can be split again.

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/sync/base/user_selectable_type.cc;l=63;drc=aec2b547f897594236bef8285c629fbafa61c4d6



Let's look at what other logic is currently being shared by 2 types:



1. Wiping of account storage settings:



Only needs to happen once, it can live in the PASSWORDS controller.

It's also going away soon-ish.

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/password_manager/core/browser/sync/credential_model_type_controller.cc;l=79-108;drc=ba4330ad08ffeef7b635dbd0bfe9ebcf52d13891



2. Forbidding transport mode for explicit passphrase users outside iOS:



This applies to both types, so the logic is kept in both controllers.

(There's no corresponding UI to enter the passphrase, so this spares

unnecessarily downloading data which will never be decrypted.

In fact, the same goes for all types supporting encryption so it

should probably be done centrally).

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/password_manager/core/browser/sync/credential_model_type_controller.cc;l=63-72;drc=ba4330ad08ffeef7b635dbd0bfe9ebcf52d13891

entry.title: [ios] Allow the app to perform long operation on startup
entry.content:
As part of launching the optimised session restoration storage, the

app will have to migrate the data on disk from the legacy format to

the optimised format.



This migration requires converting all data and writing it to disk

which can takes a while for users with thousands of tabs (of which

we have some).



Change MainController to allow to "block" the app initialisation

without being killed by the watchdog during the migration. This is

done by presenting a LaunchScreenViewController on all SceneStates

while the migration happen on a background thread and the once the

migration complete the app finally transition to the next startup

stage.



This CL adds the code that install the LaunchScreenViewController

and an helper method to invoke the asynchronous code responsible

for the migration. It does not add the migration itself (this will

happen in a followup CL).

entry.title: [Mac] Consider a frame audible when silent audio is playing
entry.content:
This is a temporary workaround for a priority inversion that happens

when the echo cancellation processing times out waiting for an audio

sample of a backgrounded renderer, which can happen when a renderer

is playing silent audio.



This is prevented with this change as renderers playing silent

audio will no longer get backgrounded.



Note that WebContents audibility (and the tab indicator) is not

impacted by this change. The audibility state of RenderFrameHostImpl

is used exclusively to control the priority of renderers.



This change is also no-op, as we currently do not enable renderer

backgrounding on MacOS yet.
